T1  - Valuation of general contingent claims: Existence, uniqueness, and comparisons of solutions
AU  - Gleit, Alan
JO  - Journal of Financial Economics
VL  - 6
IS  - 1
SP  - 71
EP  - 87
PY  - 1978
DA  - 1978/03/01/
SN  - 0304-405X
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-405X(78)90021-1
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0304405X78900211
AB  - The Black-Scholes equation for the price u(x,t) of a call option for a single share of common stock with dividend policy d(x,t) is 12σ2x2uxx+(rx−d(x,t))ux−ru−ut=0, 0<x, 0<t<T, with boundary conditions u(x,0)=max(0,x−E), 0≤x, u(0,t)=0, 0≤t≤T. The coefficients are unbounded and the equation is not uniformly parabolic. We prove an existence (and recall a uniqueness) theorem for a class of equations with boundary conditions that includes the Black-Scholes equation. These may be used to show that an American option must, or will not, sell for the same price as a European option.
